TRIP COMMENTS: Here with Jim Pike, prior to when construction had been begun on the closed MCAS Tustin base.  Wide open fields that extended as much as 1.4 miles from north to south and a little over a mile from west to east (very crude measurements on Google Earth).  We scanned for birds with binoculars and scopes from the west end of Warner, off Jamboree, on the "southeast" side of the base, as well as from Barranca (on the "south).  Weather: High, thin clouds (50% cover). Mild breeze, which winds becoming 5-10 mph, SW in later afternoon.  Temperature in the high 60s to about 70 (deg F).  40s overnight.----We had decided to check out the base due to a Rough-legged Hawk being reported here, with somewhat unconvincing details, by one of the local birders, and we figured we'd give it a look.
SPECIES COMMENTS: Pretty amazing:  two Bald and two Golden eagles seen here during this visit!  My notes on this observation states:  "Two Bald Eagles! Jim first picked one out, shortly after he arriced, and just before I walked up.  This while viewing from the west end of Warner Ave.  This was an apparent juvenile bird (dark body, head and tail, whitish frosting on underwing coverts).  Flying low over field possibly as much as a half, to 2/3 mile from our vantage spot. After a bit I noticed that it suddenly engaged a second large raptor, which had been on the ground, unnoticed by us due to being behind a gentle rise in the terrain, along with taller weeds (mustard). At that point I could see that the SECOND bird was ALSO a Bald Eagle!!  There were apparently scuffling over a carcass, though couldn't see what it was.  Several CORAs were here as well, and RTHAs in near vicinity.  The second Bald Eagle had extensive white on breast and belly, and underwings, though details difficult to see due to distance.  Maybe two of the three Bald Eagles seen at Irvine Lake recently?"

LOCALITY: Lake Cachuma - narrows and east end
TRIP COMMENTS: Observers: Melissa Kelly, Dave Compton. --Area covered: Dropped off at the entrance to the Narrows on the south shore (at the northern tip of the peninsula) and birded about 300 m southeast to observation pt. From here, each of us birded at least once over the next three hours to the eastern tip of the peninsula, another 200 m se, while the other observer stayed at our observation point. Our views from the south shore, particularly at our observation point, afforded us good views of the narrows below. We were visiting this location as part of the annual Bald Eagle count conducted on the lake. --Lake conditions: The lake level was approximately 35 ft below capacity. Water extended through the length of the narrows, but there were large areas of mudflats over much of the area. Only a small amount of water and wet ground extended eastward into the east end of the lake. Much of this area was difficult to see from the road along the edge of the lake.

Extracted from the Eastern Sierra Birds archive (https://www.esaudubon.org/birds/archives/b4c/00000102.htm) on 8/29/2024. Despite Crowley Reservoir being 50% frozen over, Jon Dunn's ESAS field trip on 4 Dec managed 41 species. 17 participants spent the clear, calm, chilly (24F-38F) day birding the NW arm, delta, and marina. Highlights were the continuing Bewick's Swan, first reported by Tom Wurster on 7 Nov, along with another 110 Tundra Swans, a late American White Pelican, 5 geese species: White-fronted (5), Snow (5), Ross's (10), Canada (200), and Aleutian/Cackling (9). Also, two adult Bald Eagles and 1 immature Golden Eagle, 4 Dunlin flying by, 15 Greater Yellowlegs, and 2 Rough-legged Hawks.

With Dave Quady.  Marysville CBC.  Our Christmas count area was south of Hwy 20 and north of the Yuba River, east of Marysville, all in Yuba county. It extended east to past Brown's Valley road, to a road on the right leading to a quarry. Organized by Tim Manolis. In addition to birds herein, Dave saw a Phainopepla in Hammond Co Park. Our route started with owling in the park, then we did an extra-limital area bounded by Loma Rica, Kibby and Lincoln from 7:15 to 8:30. Our area started with 6123 Hwy 20, a road to Garcia Gravel to 10:15, then Hammond Co Park to noon (along the river a considerable distance). We did Hallwood Blvd and the River to 2:20 and Plantz and Powell to 3:45, ending at Walnut to 4:20.
